To demonstrate the versatility of the FDTD technique, it was also applied in the modeling of horn antennas in \cite{Balanis_Finite-difference_time-domain_antenna_radiation}. For the horns, smaller grid resolutions were required to achieve results which compared well with measurements, especially in the back region. Two different FDTD grid resolutions were used to compute the principal patterns of a pyramidal horn; $\lambda/22$ and $\lambda/28$. The physical dimensions of the horn used were $\rho_H=10.65\lambda$, $\rho_E=9.7\lambda$, $\theta_H=11.16^\circ$ \& $\theta_E=9.09^\circ$ for the frequency 10.0 GHz as shown in the Fig.~\ref{Fig:geo_fdtd_horn_all_1}. The grid size of $\lambda/22$ was chosen because it subdivided the X-band waveguide into an integral number of cells ($18\times8$ cells). Their cell size of $\lambda/28$ corresponded to the smallest cell resolution of the FDTD grid that was allowed on a CRAY-2 with 64 mega words of memory. They found that the main differences in the two computations occurred in the backside of the antenna where the radiation intensity is very low compared to that in the forward direction. The CPU times for each case were 10200 s when a grid size of $\lambda/28$ was used, and 6,500 s when the grid size was increased to $\lambda/22$. In both cases, a distance of $\lambda$ was allowed between the antenna surface and the outer boundary of the FDTD problem space. 

The principal E- and H-plane patterns of an X-band pyramidal horn, corresponding to a grid size of $\lambda/28$, were compared with measurements in \cite[Figs. 12 and 13]{Balanis_Finite-difference_time-domain_antenna_radiation}, respectively. There FDTD results agreed very well with measurements both in the main lobes and back lobes of the patterns. In both the E and H-plane patterns, the computed and measured patterns display their largest differences toward the back region $(\theta=180^\circ)$. This difference was attributed to the supporting structure of the antenna used when the measurements were performed. This support structure was not included in their FDTD modeling. They claimed that the accuracy of the FDTD results could also be improved by increasing the distance between the antenna and the outer surface. The radiation boundary conditions imposed on the outer surface were found to perform better when the incoming wave is a plane wave. Increasing the distance between the antenna and the outer surface, however, results in an increase of the number of cells required to model the antenna.

%The staircase FDTD approach was also applied to model radiation by horn antennas. Numerical results obtained using the staircase approach were compared with measurements. These comparisons indicated that the FDTD technique can be used to analyze radiation by antennas with surfaces that cannot be resolved using either a cubic or rectangular grid. Using a cell size of $\lambda/22$, the computations of the FDTD technique are in good agreement with measurements in the forward region of the antenna. In the back region of the antenna, where the radiation intensity was low, more accurate results are obtained by using a smaller grid ($\lambda/28$).


%\section{Balanis-94 \cite{Tirkas_Contour_Path_FDTD_Pyramidal_Horns_E_Plane}}

A 20-dB standard gain pyramidal horn antenna with conducting inner walls was analyzed using the contour path FDTD technique \cite{Tirkas_Contour_Path_FDTD_Pyramidal_Horns_E_Plane}. They compared the computed E- and H-plane gain patterns, respectively, of the pyramidal horn with measurements at 10 GHz. They found very good agreement between the computed and measured results over a dynamic range of 60 dB. The computed gain patterns agreed very well with the measured ones when a standard cell size of $\lambda/12$ was used (0.254 cm). The overall FDTD grid used for this problem was 76 x 60 x 142 cells. This simulation was run for 40 cycles to reach steady state and took about 2500 s on an IBM-RISC/6000 computer for computing the E- and H-plane gain patterns over $360^0$ at 10 steps.

